  "description": "Repairable 2oo3 pump station: three pumps, any two of which meet demand. Unlike the redundant-power example this chain has no absorbing state, so it is irreducible — steady-state availability, MTBF/MTTR and frequency all converge to meaningful values (an absorbing model drives them to 0). Per pump λ = 1e-3/h (MTBF 1000 h), MTTR 8 h, and a single repair crew, so pumps are restored one at a time (S0 → S1 → S2 → OK). Four failure mechanisms compete: independent wear (3λ → 2λ → λ as redundancy is consumed), a β = 2% common-cause failure (shared suction header / power bus) that takes all three pumps at once and needs a 24 h recovery, a monthly proof test (720 h) that deliberately bypasses one pump for 4 h — during which a second failure (2λ) drops the station straight to S1 — and a spurious trip (5e-4/h) that stops the station but resets in an hour. UP = OK, S2, PM (two or more pumps available); DOWN = S1, S0, CCF, SPUR. Try: availability (~0.999), frequency/MTBF/MTTR (the mix of 1 h spurious trips and 24 h common-cause outages is what makes MTTR interesting), transient availability, and sensitivity. For MTTF, mark S0 absorbing — the solver needs an absorbing state and will tell you so otherwise.",
